title: Seed Plants of Malesia and Indo-China - 28 July 2010

states: Absent, all parts colourless, white, yellowish or pale brown tinges
characters.name: Plant with green pigment (chlorophyll)

states: With a resinous exudate or becoming resinous when dried
characters.name: Plant resinous

states: not as above, or without sap
characters.name: Sap colour

states: Plant growing independently (but could be an epiphyte, saprophyte or carnivorous)
characters.name: Parasitism

states: With special structures for housing ants
Without special structures for housing ants
characters.name: Ant plants

states: Branches or stems conspicuously thickened at the nodes
characters.name: Swollen nodes

states: Armed with thorns or spines on the stems, leaves or other organs
Unarmed, without any thorns or spines
characters.name: Plant armed or not

states: Divided into more than one blade (compound)
characters.name: Type of leaf

states: 3 or more leaflets arising from 1 point (ternate, trifoliolate or palmate)
in pairs along each side of a common axis, i.e. pinnate
pinnate with the main axis also pinnately divided, i.e. bipinnate
characters.name: Type of compound leaf

states: By base of blade but without a stalk (sessile)
characters.name: Leaf attachment to stem

states: Towards the centre of the blade (peltate)
At the base of the blade
characters.name: Leaf-stalk attachment to blade

states: Swollen at the base and/or the apex
characters.name: Leaf-stalk shape

states: Red when young (often not visible when dried)
Withering red (often not visible when dried)
characters.name: Leaf colour

states: Present on the leaf-stalk or leaf-blade
Absent from the leaf-stalk and leaf-blade
characters.name: Leaf glands

states: Present, visible on strongly backlit leaf-blade
Absent, not visible on strongly backlit leaf-blade
characters.name: Leaf-blade with transluscent dots (and dashes)

states: Present, visible as raised pale lumps (with handlens)
characters.name: Cystoliths on leaf-blade surface

states: Present - some flowers having only male or only female parts
Absent - all flowers have both male and female parts
characters.name: Unisexual flowers

states: Perianth of two whorls; sepals and petals
Segments of the perianth sequentially intergrading from sepals to petals
Perianth of sepals only, petals only or tepals only
characters.name: Presence of sepals and petals or tepals

states: Not fused, all petals or tepals free
Partly fused, some petals or tepals joined, others free
All petal or tepal parts joined
characters.name: Fusion of petals or tepals
Number of sepals plus petals, or number of tepals (perianth segments)

states: less than the number of the inner perianth whorl
same number as the inner perianth whorl
double the number of the inner perianth whorl
three times the number of the inner perianth whorl
more than three times the number of the inner perianth whorl
characters.name: Number of fertile stamens relative to the inner perianth whorl

states: Dehiscent, splitting open to release the seeds
Indehiscent, if splitting then not releasing the seeds (schizocarpic)
characters.name: Dehiscence of fruit
Mode of splitting of schizocarpic fruits

states: Present, spiny, rugose or with soft processes
characters.name: Fruit surface spiny or muricate

states: Present, usually longitudinal ridge or ridges
characters.name: Ridges on fruit surface

states: Absent, derived from a single flower
characters.name: Fruit originating from several flowers

states: Large woody fruit with seeds in an unordered arrangement
characters.name: Seeds scattered inside woody fruit

states: A round capsule that splits at the apex
characters.name: Fruit an apically splitting capsule

states: leaves imparipinnate (they have a top leaflet)
leaves paripinnate (they do not have a leaflet at the top)
as in 2, but the rachis is extended (no leaflet but only an\par{}extension of the rachis)\par{}
characters.name: Compound leaves paripinnate or imparipinnate
Arrangement of leaflets in compound leaves
Attachment of leaflets to rachis in compound leaves
Number of pairs of pinnae (in compound leaves)
Number of leaflets in compound leaves (per pinna, if no pinna present than in leaf)

states: One or more filaments attached to petals
characters.name: Stamens attached to petals

states: Stamens fused to form a tube, sometimes only at the base
Stamens fused but open at one side, perhaps one stamen free
Stamens fused, but vexillary stamen free at base (basal fenestrae)
characters.name: Staminal tube
